{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"303bc25d-2b80-43a8-b6fa-a72d968e9815","content":"## What's Happening\n\n**.NET 11 raised the x86-64 baseline CPU requirement.** The runtime now requires instruction sets that your 2012-era hardware doesn't support.\n\n### The x86-64 microarchitecture levels\n\n| Level | Key Instructions | Earliest Intel | Earliest AMD |\n|-------|-----------------|---------------|-------------|\n| **v1** | SSE, SSE2 | Pentium 4 (2003) | Athlon 64 (2003) |\n| **v2** | SSE4.2, POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B | Nehalem (2008) | Bulldozer (2011) |\n| **v3** | AVX, AVX2, FMA, BMI1/2 | **Haswell (2013)** | Excavator (2015) |\n| **v4** | AVX-512 | Skylake-X (2017) | Zen 4 (2022) |\n\n.NET has progressively raised its baseline:\n- **.NET 10** required **x86-64-v2** (your 2012 hardware passed this)\n- **.NET 11** raised to **x86-64-v3**, which requires **AVX2** — introduced with Haswell in **2013**\n\nYour 2012 node is likely Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge, which supports v2 but **not** v3. That's what triggers the startup error.\n\n### Your other platforms are fine\n\n- **Surface Pro X (SQ1/ARM64):** Meets the ARMv8.0-A baseline .NET requires.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Cortex-A72):** Also ARMv8-A compliant — no issue.\n\n### Options to fix\n\n1. **Replace the 2012 hardware** with Haswell-era (2013+) or newer CPUs.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10** (LTS) for nodes that can't be upgraded — it supports v2-level hardware.\n3. **Check your fleet** — run this on each Linux node to see what level it supports:\n   ```bash\n   # Checks for AVX2 support (the key v3 gate)\n   grep -q avx2 /proc/cpuinfo && echo \"x86-64-v3 OK\" || echo \"MISSING AVX2 — won't run .NET 11\"\n   ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"466cb0fb-958b-4557-ba91-5e55b47b19c6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's evolving hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nLet me explain what's happening:\n\nStarting with .NET 9 (and reinforced in later versions), the .NET runtime has been raising baseline CPU requirements. Specifically, for x86-64 Linux:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier: required only the original x86-64 baseline (SSE, SSE2)\n- .NET 9+: started requiring SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2 as baseline\n\n\n- This aligns with the x86-64-v2 microarchitecture level, which also includes POPCNT\n\nThe user is upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, which are hypothetical future versions, but the pattern of raising baseline CPU requirements is real and ongoing. SSE4.2 and POPCNT are available on 2012-era Intel chips like Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge, so x86-64-v2 wouldn't be the breaking point. But x86-64-v3 requires AVX2, which didn't arrive until Haswell in 2013—so that's where 2012 hardware would start failing.\n\nThe most likely explanation is that .NET 11 bumped the baseline to x86-64-v3, which their older system can't support. Though I should consider what Microsoft has actually announced—the realistic progression would be raising to x86-64-v2 first as a modest increase, with x86-64-v3 coming later. is very common since AVX2 didn't arrive until 2013 with Haswell. So the most likely scenario is that .NET 11 raised the baseline to x86-64-v3, which explains why 2012 hardware fails. For the other platforms, Windows ARM64 should be fine since the SQ1 supports ARMv8.0-A, and the Raspberry Pi 4's Cortex-A72 should also meet the baseline requirements. x86-64-v3 requires AVX2 and other features that only arrived with Haswell in 2013, so 2012 hardware definitely won't support it. That's likely what's causing the error.","outputTokens":2190,"requestId":"E033:3D4AC3:7717344:83C4B6D:69F405DC"},"id":"552434cf-b8a3-4b71-9253-89070a8e7592","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:46:47.318Z","parentId":"3ceb8ec5-f727-4e0c-8456-801a0fff3017"}
